## 3. Revised Parsing Architecture

### The Real Problem (Acknowledged)

Emails are **NOT consistent**:
- Some banks omit merchant
- Some include HTML formatting
- Some have partial data
- Formats change without notice

### Multi-Tier Parsing Strategy

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    EMAIL["Raw Email"] --> DETECT["Sender Detection<br/>Which bank?"]
    DETECT --> REGISTRY["Parser Registry"]
    REGISTRY --> BANK["Bank-Specific Parser<br/>(Rule-based regex)"]
    BANK -->|Success| CONF["Confidence Check"]
    BANK -->|Partial| HEUR["Heuristic Parser<br/>(Fuzzy extraction)"]
    HEUR -->|Success| CONF
    HEUR -->|Fail| AI["AI Fallback<br/>(LLM extraction)"]
    AI --> CONF
    CONF -->|≥ 0.7| STORE["Store Transaction"]
    CONF -->|< 0.7| FLAG["Store + Flag for Review"]
    BANK -->|Total Fail| DLQ["Dead Letter Queue"]
```

### Parser Versioning

```
Transaction stored with:
  parser_version: 3
  
When parser improves to v4:
  → Re-run on raw emails
  → Update transactions
  → Keep old version in audit log
```

### Bank-Specific Parser Registry

```python
# Conceptual design
class ParserRegistry:
    parsers = {
        "alerts@hdfcbank.com": HDFCParser,
        "alerts@sbi.co.in": SBIParser,
        "noreply@icicibank.com": ICICIParser,
    }
    fallback = GenericParser
    ai_fallback = LLMParser  # only when confidence < 0.5
```

---

## 4. Revised Deduplication Strategy

### Multi-Level Approach

| Level | Match Criteria | Action |
|-------|---------------|--------|
| **Strong** | `ref_id` matches exactly | Skip (100% duplicate) |
| **Medium** | `amount + merchant + date + account` within ±5 min | Skip (95% duplicate) |
| **Weak** | `amount + merchant + date` same day | Flag for review |
| **None** | No match | Store as new |

### Fingerprint Computation

```
fingerprint = SHA256(
    amount + "|" + 
    date + "|" + 
    merchant_normalized + "|" + 
    ref_id_or_empty + "|" +
    account_last4
)
```

---

## 5. User Feedback Loop (NEW)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    DASH["Dashboard"] -->|"Wrong category"| CORRECT["User Correction"]
    CORRECT --> STORE["Store Correction"]
    STORE --> RULES["Update Category Rules"]
    STORE --> ALIAS["Update Merchant Aliases"]
    RULES --> PARSER["Improved Parsing"]
    ALIAS --> PARSER
```

### How Corrections Improve the System

| User Action | System Learning |
|------------|----------------|
| "This isn't Swiggy, it's Zomato" | Add alias mapping |
| "This should be Groceries, not Food" | Update category rule |
| "Wrong amount" | Flag parser for this bank format |
| "This is not a transaction" | Improve filter engine |

---

## 6. Confidence Handling in UI (NEW)

| Confidence | UI Treatment |
|-----------|-------------|
| ≥ 0.85 | ✅ Auto-accepted, shown normally |
| 0.60–0.84 | ⚠️ Subtle warning icon, editable |
| < 0.60 | 🔴 "Needs Review" badge, prominent edit button |

---

## 7. Error Handling & DLQ (NEW)

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    PARSE["Parse Attempt"] -->|Success| STORE["Store Transaction"]
    PARSE -->|Failure| DLQ["Dead Letter Queue"]
    DLQ --> RETRY["Auto-Retry (3x with backoff)"]
    RETRY -->|Success| STORE
    RETRY -->|Final Fail| MANUAL["Flag for Manual Review"]
    MANUAL -->|Parser Updated| REPROCESS["Re-process with new parser"]
```

### Non-Negotiable Rules
- Never block pipeline on errors
- Always store raw email regardless of parse result
- Log every failure with error details
- Failed emails get re-processed when parser improves

---

## 8. Sync Strategy (Revised)

### Use Gmail `historyId` (Not Polling)

```
First sync:
  → Fetch last 100 emails
  → Store historyId

Subsequent syncs:
  → Use history.list(startHistoryId)
  → Only get NEW emails
  → Far more efficient
```

### Sync Tracking

Every sync run logged:
```json
{
  "id": "sync_001",
  "start_time": "2026-05-05T10:00:00",
  "end_time": "2026-05-05T10:00:03",
  "emails_fetched": 12,
  "emails_processed": 8,
  "emails_failed": 1,
  "errors": [{"email_id": "...", "error": "Amount not found"}],
  "status": "completed"
}
```

